<Linux device driver for AVerMedia CX511H HDMI HD Capture Card>

	This is the Linux device driver released for AVerMedia CX511H HDMI HD Capture Card with PCI-Express Mini Card interface.

<Quick install/uninstall>

	1. Unpack the tarball:

	2. Install and load the module (as root or with sudo):

		# sudo make install
		# sudo modprobe cx511h
        # sudo -i
        # sudo echo cx511h >> /etc/modules (just for first time installation))

	3. Uninstall and unload the moudle (as root or with sudo):
                (makesure unbind the device before uninstall,ex. sudo echo -n "0000:01:00.0" >unbind) 
		# sudo modprobe -r cx511h
		# sudo make uninstall

<Check driver version>

        driver version
                # sudo cat /sys/module/cx511h/version

<Check chip version>

        chip version
                # dmesg | grep chip_version

<Support input source>

	V4L2 input index: HDMI=0 <index=0>

<Supported pixel format>

	YUYV/RGB - Raw data

<VLC AP>
        Fill value to the column of width, height on Advanced Options
        
        example : input signal 1920x1080

        1. original in/out: set width = 1920 and height = 1080
        2. scaler down: set width = 1280 and height = 720
	 

<V4L2 utils>

	replace '$' with your device index

	1. Install v4l-utils

		# apt-get install v4l-utils (as root or with sudo)

	2. Check cm311h video device index

		# v4l2-ctl --list-devices

	3. Set video input 

		# v4l2-ctl --device=/dev/video$ --set-input=<index>

	4. Set output video format

		# v4l2-ctl --device=/dev/video$ --set-fmt-video=width=<width>,height=<height>,pixelformat=YUYV

	        or default video size

		# v4l2-ctl --device=/dev/video$ --set-fmt-video=width=0,height=0,pixelformat=<RGB or YUYV>

	example:

	1. Downscale to 1280x720

		# v4l2-ctl --device=/dev/video0 --set-fmt-video=width=1280,height=720,pixelformat=YUYV

	2. Default resolution 1920x1080

		# v4l2-ctl --device=/dev/video0 --set-fmt-video=width=0,height=0,pixelformat=YUYV


<Supported output resolutions>

	640x480
	720x480
	720x576
	800x600
	1024x768
	1280x720
	1280x800
	1280x1024
	1360x768
	1440x900
	1680x1050
	1920x1080

<Supported v4l2 control>

	replace '$' with your device index

	V42L_CID_BRIGHTNESS
		min=-128,max=127,default=0

	V4L2 CID_SATURATION
		min=0,max=255,default=128

	V4L2_CID_CONTRAST
		min=0,max=255,default=128

	V4L2_CID_HUE
		min=0,max=255,default=0

	
	1. Use v4l2-ctl to query control

		# v4l2-ctl --device=/dev/video$ -L

	2. Set control

	example

		# v4l2-ctl --device=/dev/video$ --set-ctrl=brightness=100


